  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>Elsewhere on this bug, there are tips on how to reproduce this bug.

The most reasonable fix would probably be to sort the list of projects that you 
get when you click "More projects" alphabetically, case-insensitive, by name.

You'll probably need to use Django's order_by() function to get that to work, 
and you might need to import a data snapshot to get any projects to show up 
here. (Look in the docs about how to import a data snapshot. Also, doing that 
import can take 20-60 minutes.)

The code for this *probably* is mysite/search/views.py , the search_index() 
function. It is one seriously long function, but with any luck you won't have to 
understand all of it.

Do look at the template, too! That's mysite/search/templates/search/search.html 
. The quickest way to solve this is probably to:

* Look at the template, and understand what variable name is being passed into 
the template

* Look in the function, and figure out what is filling out that variable

* See if you can fix the issue by adding a call to .order_by() something... 
maybe order_by('name') or order_by('project__name').

Marking as bitesize, but this is sort of mouthful size.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
